  "prompt": "If [math]1\\circ4=5[/math] and [math]2\\circ5=12[/math] and [math]3\\circ6=21[/math] then what is [math]8\\circ11[/math]? Fun\u2026",
  "response": "Let the operation $\\circ$ be defined as $a \\circ b = f(a,b)$ for some function $f$.\nWe are given the following:\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item $1 \\circ 4 = 5$\n    \\item $2 \\circ 5 = 12$\n    \\item $3 \\circ 6 = 21$\n\\end{itemize}\nWe want to find $8 \\circ 11$.\nLet's examine the relationships between $a$, $b$, and the result $a \\circ b$.\nWe have $a \\circ b = f(a,b)$.\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item $1 \\circ 4 = 5$\n    \\item $2 \\circ 5 = 12$\n    \\item $3 \\circ 6 = 21$\n\\end{itemize}\nWe look for a pattern. Notice that\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item $1 \\cdot 4 + 1 = 5$\n    \\item $2 \\cdot 5 + 2 = 12$\n    \\item $3 \\cdot 6 + 3 = 21$\n\\end{itemize}\nSo the pattern seems to be $a \\circ b = ab + a = a(b+1)$.\nNow we can compute $8 \\circ 11$ using this pattern:\n$$8 \\circ 11 = 8(11+1) = 8(12) = 96$$\nLet's also look at\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item $1 \\circ 4 = (1+1)(4-1) - 1 = 2(3) - 1 = 5$\n    \\item $2 \\circ 5 = (2+1)(5-1) - 0 = 3(4) = 12$\n    \\item $3 \\circ 6 = (3+1)(6-1) + 1 = 4(5) + 1 = 21$\n\\end{itemize}\nAnother possibility is $a \\circ b = a(b+1)$. Then\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item $1 \\circ 4 = 1(4+1) = 5$\n    \\item $2 \\circ 5 = 2(5+1) = 2(6) = 12$\n    \\item $3 \\circ 6 = 3(6+1) = 3(7) = 21$\n\\end{itemize}\nUsing this pattern, we have $8 \\circ 11 = 8(11+1) = 8(12) = 96$.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{96}$",
